[h1]GK Raiding — Changelog[/h1]

[h2]Unreleased[/h2]

[h3]Pop Raiding Escalation[/h3]
[list]
[*]Pop raiding now uses a tiered system. Initial raids capture a small portion of the target population. Spending Influence authorizes deeper raids, with each tier taking progressively more.
[*]When a tier is filled, the war leader chooses how to proceed:
  [list]
  [*][b]Plunder wars:[/b] Hold position, authorize deeper raids, switch to resource pillaging, or demand tribute
  [*][b]Emancipation wars:[/b] Hold position, authorize deeper raids, or demand the abolition of slavery
  [*][b]Emancipation with Robots Only policy:[/b] Demand full synthetic citizen rights instead
  [/list]
[*]Reaping bypasses all limits and prevents surrender.
[*]Pops are now taken proportionally across all eligible species rather than draining one group at a time.
[*]A notification popup appears when raiding seizes the last population of an empire.
[/list]

[h3]Tribute[/h3]
[list]
[*]During plunder wars, raiders can demand a resource payment from the defender in exchange for ceasing raids.
[*]The defender chooses how to pay: Energy Credits, Alloys, or a split of both. Bio-ship empires demand Food instead of Energy.
[*]If accepted, the raider's Influence is refunded. If refused or ignored after 3 months, raiding continues.
[*]Paying tribute ends pop raids against that raider but does not end the war.
[/list]

[h3]Influence Costs[/h3]
[list]
[*]The cost to authorize deeper raids now scales with how significant the raid is relative to the raider's empire. Raiding a small neighbor stays cheap. Depopulating a major rival costs substantially more Influence.
[*]With sufficient intel on the target, the escalation report shows how many eligible pops remain.
[/list]

[h3]Civics and War Goals[/h3]
[list]
[*]Removed Robo-Liberators, Synthetic Liberation Corp, and Freedom Directive civics. Existing saves keep a deprecated placeholder until the player reforms their government.
[*]Removed the Robo-Liberation war goal. Robot liberation is now handled through Emancipation with the Robots Only raiding policy.
[*]Emancipation now has its own casus belli, separate from Despoliation.
[/list]

[h3]Reaping[/h3]
[list]
[*]Reaping is now a raiding focus policy option rather than always being available.
[*]Only Barbaric Despoiler civics and Hive Bodysnatcher can select Reaping. Nihilistic Acquisition empires use the escalation system to reach full depopulation instead.
[*]Declaring a Reaping war now carries a much heavier galaxy-wide opinion penalty.
[/list]

[h3]Hive Mind Support[/h3]
[list]
[*]The Hive Bodysnatcher civic now grants access to pop raiding, the raiding bombardment stance, and the Reaping war goal.
[/list]

[h3]Opinion[/h3]
[list]
[*]Galaxy-wide opinion penalty for raided pops, applied consistently across all raiding war types.
[*]Authorizing deeper raids carries an additional galaxy-wide opinion cost.
[*]The target empire always suffers an extra opinion hit on top of the galaxy-wide penalty.
[*]Egalitarian and xenophile empires react more harshly. Empires that practice purging themselves are less bothered.
[/list]
